19 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY Section 2, Chapter 492, O.S.L.
20 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1210.900), is amended to read as
21 follows:
22 Section 1210.900. A. Sections 2 This section through 8 Section
23 1210.907 of this act title shall be known and may be cited as the
24 “Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency Act”.
Req. No. 17365 Page 11

1 B. The Legislature finds that it is essential for children
2 enrolled in the public schools in this state to develop strong
3 mathematical proficiency early and consistently. The Legislature
4 further finds that clear and visible goals, assessments to determine
5 math proficiency at each school, the use of scientifically based and
6 researched methodologies in math instruction, along with regular and
7 periodic measurements of school math improvement, and accountability
8 at each level of the educational system will result in a significant
9 increase in the number of children performing at or above grade
10 level in mathematics.
11 C. The purpose of the Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency
12 Act is to ensure that student achievement in math is encouraged and
13 progression from one grade to another is determined, in part, upon
14 proficiency in mathematics, that school district board of education
15 policies facilitate promotion of advanced math instruction and
16 intervention services to address student math needs, and that each
17 student and his or her parent or legal guardian be informed of the
18 student’s progress in mathematics.
19 D. Each public school district in this state shall ensure that
20 all students receive a well-rounded education focused on building
21 deep foundations in mathematics, reading, and writing. The State
22 Board of Education shall encourage school districts to integrate the
23 teaching of the other curricular areas in subject matter standards
24
Req. No. 17365 Page 12

1 adop ted by the Board with the instruction of mathematics, reading,
2 and writing.
3 E. All teachers of mathematics in the public schools in this
4 state shall have access to training in evidence-based professional
5 development programs to deepen their content knowledge, learn
6 specific effective and impactful teaching strategies, and develop
7 productive dispositions toward math, and then incorporate into
8 instruction the foundational elements of math instruction, including
9 the development of grade-level appropriate mathematical proficiency
10 which is a combination of real-world problem-solving skills,
11 procedural fluency, conceptual understanding, and productive
12 dispositions.
13 F. 1. There is hereby created within the State Department of
14 Education an Office of Mathematics Improvement, which shall be
15 created within ninety (90) days of the effective date of this act.
16 The Superintendent of Public Instruction shall appoint a Director of
17 the Office of Mathematics Improvement whose exclusive focus shall be
18 mathematics instruction for students in grades kindergarten through
19 five. The Director shall have experience in administrative duties,
20 in teaching mathematics in a public or private elementary school,
21 and as an elementary mathematics specialist, coach, or
22 administrator.
23 2. The Director of the Office of Mathematics Improvement shall:
24
Req. No. 17365 Page 13

1 a. monitor implementation of screening instruments,
2 diagnostic assessments, and formative assessments for
3 grades kindergarten through five to identify students
4 in need of support for key numeracy concepts,
5 b. recommend training and support for educators for the
6 effective implementation and interpretation of
7 diagnostic tools. The diagnostic tool shall be used
8 with students who have been identified with
9 deficiencies in mathematics based on screening
10 instruments, diagnostic assessments, formative
11 assessments, benchmark assessments, teacher
12 observation, or any combination thereof,
13 c. designate a team of educators to explore the
14 connection between difficulties with number sense and
15 dyscalculia as well as possible effective screening
16 instruments,
17 d. commit necessary resources to understanding the needs
18 of students struggling with number sense or
19 dyscalculia, or both, before implementing
20 instructional practices or assessments that could
21 adversely affect student learning,
22 e. monitor the implementation and progress of summer
23 mathematics academies,
24
Req. No. 17365 Page 14

1 f. recommend changes and improvements to any professional
2 development providers and public schools in this state
3 based on data collected and analyzed by the Office of
4 Mathematics Improvement, and
5 g. monitor the implementation and progress of the
6 Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency Act.
