3 supplemental funding reflecting the increased
4 instructional intensity required at the Tier 3 level.
5 2. Supplemental weighted funding received pursuant to this
6 subsection shall be used exclusively for intervention services
7 beyond Tier 1 core instruction including:
8 a. additional instructional time devoted to math
9 intervention,
10 b. reduced instructional group sizes necessary to deliver
11 intensive instruction,
12 c. specialized instructional materials and intervention
13 programs aligned with scientifically based math
14 research,
15 d. compensation for educators delivering intervention
16 services, and
17 e. professional development necessary to ensure educators
18 providing intervention services have extensive
19 training in scientifically based math research
20 including how students learn mathematical concepts;
21 training in providing explicit and systematic
22 instruction in real-world problem-solving skills,
23 procedural fluency, conceptual understanding, and
24 productive dispositions; implementing math strategies
Req. No. 17365 Page 25

1 that research has shown to be successful in improving
2 math proficiency among students with math
3 difficulties; and courses leading to a micro-
4 credential in mathematics.
5 3. Students shall be counted for purposes of supplemental
6 weighted funding only when the school district has documented and
7 electronically reported to the State Department of Education that
8 the student is receiving intervention services consistent with the
9 level of instructional intensity required at the applicable tier.
10 4. School districts shall maintain documentation demonstrating:
11 a. identification of the student through an approved
12 screening instrument and supporting diagnostic or
13 progress-monitoring data,
14 b. implementation of an intervention plan specifying the
15 instructional approach, frequency, duration, and group
16 size of intervention services, and
17 c. ongoing progress monitoring used to determine the
18 effectiveness of the intervention and inform
19 instructional adjustments.
20 5. Students shall not generate supplemental weighted funding
21 unless intervention services are provided beyond Tier 1 core
22 instruction. The State Department of Education may review
23 intervention documentation and program implementation to verify
24
Req. No. 17365 Page 26

1 elig ibility for supplemental weighted funding allocated pursuant to
2 this section.
3 6. The State Board of Education shall promulgate rules
4 establishing reasonable expectations for the proportion of students
5 receiving supplemental and intensive services within an MTSS
6 framework.
7 7. When the reported percentage of students receiving Tier 2 or
8 Tier 3 intervention services significantly exceeds expected ranges,
9 the State Department of Education may require additional
10 documentation or provide technical assistance to ensure intervention
11 services are implemented within the instructional intensity required
12 at each tier.
13 C. The State Department of Education shall approve and publish
14 a list of professional development programs that are evidence-based
15 and directly address the cognitive science of how students learn
16 mathematics for which districts are permitted to use the funds
17 received pursuant to this section.
18 D. If a teacher attends and completes a professional
19 development institute in elementary math approved by the Commission
20 for Educational Quality and Accountability during the summer or when
21 school is not in session, the teacher may receive a stipend equal to
22 the amount of the cost for a substitute teacher, based on the amount
23 of funds allocated 1. To encourage continuous improvement in
24 student math outcomes and to support the sustainability of effective
Req. No. 17365 Page 27

1 inte rvention services, the State Board of Education shall allocate
2 up to thirty percent (30%) of funds appropriated for the purposes of
3 this section for math improvement incentives and shall promulgate
4 rules establishing criteria for determining eligibility for such
5 incentives, which shall include demonstration of measurable
6 improvement in student math performance.
7 2. Math improvement incentives may include recognition of:
8 a. students who demonstrate sufficient progress to exit
9 Tier 3 intensive intervention,
10 b. students who demonstrate sufficient progress to exit
11 Tier 2 supplemental intervention, and
12 c. school districts or school sites that demonstrate
13 measurable reductions in the number or percentage of
14 students requiring supplemental or intensive
15 intervention.
16 SECTION 5. AMENDATORY Section 5, Chapter 492, O.S.L.
17 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1210.903), is amended to read as
18 follows:
19 Section 1210.903. A. If a teacher determines that a student in
20 second, third, fourth, and fifth grade is performing above grade
21 level in mathematics by the start of the second quarter of the
22 school year, the parent or legal guardian of the student shall be
23 notified of:
24 1. The math proficiency level of the student;
Req. No. 17365 Page 28

1 2. The program of advanced math instruction available for the
2 student; and
3 3. The potential for the student to participate in a summer
4 academy or other program designed to assist the student in excelling
5 in mathematics.
6 B. If a teacher determines that a student in second, third,
7 fourth, and or fifth grade is not performing at grade level in
8 mathematics by the start of the second quarter of the school year,
9 the parent or legal guardian of the student shall be notified of:
10 1. The math proficiency level of the student;
11 2. The program of math instruction for the student as required
12 pursuant to this act the Oklahoma Math Achievement and Proficiency
13 Act; and
14 3. The potential need for the student to participate in a
15 summer academy or other program designed to assist the student in
16 attaining grade-level math proficiency.
17 C. A teacher who determines a student in second, third, fourth,
18 and or fifth grade is exceeding or not meeting grade-level targets
19 for mathematics may, after consultation with the parent or legal
20 guardian of the student, recommend that the student participate in
21 and complete a summer academy or other program.
22 D. Summer academy programs shall be designed to ensure that
23 participating students successfully complete an advanced
24 mathematical program or grade-level competencies in mathematics to
Req. No. 17365 Page 29

1 enha nce next-grade readiness. A summer academy math program shall
2 be a program that incorporates the content of a scientifically
3 research-based professional development program administered by the
4 Commission for Educational Quality and Accountability or a
5 scientifically research-based math program administered by the State
6 Board of Education which is taught by teachers who have successfully
7 completed professional development in the math program. All summer
8 academy programs shall consist of a minimum of three (3) consecutive
9 days. The State Department of Education shall provide a list of
10 qualified entities for providing the summer academy programs to all
11 schools by April 1, 2026.
12 E. School districts may approve an option for students who are
13 unable to attend a summer academy. The optional program may
14 include, but not be limited to, an approved private provider of
15 instruction, approved computer- or Internet-based instruction, or an
16 approved program of math instruction monitored by the parent or
17 legal guardian of the student. Public school districts shall not be
18 required to pay for the optional program but shall clearly
19 communicate to the parent or legal guardian the expectations of the
20 program and any costs that may be involved.
21 F. Subject to the availability of funds, beginning one (1) year
22 after implementation of this section, the requirements of subsection
23 C of this section may be expanded to apply to students in first
24 grade. Each year thereafter, the requirements may be expanded by
Req. No. 17365 Page 30

1 one grade level until the requirements apply to kindergarten
2 students through fifth-grade students. Summer academy programs
3 shall be designed for each grade level. Nothing in this section
4 shall prevent the State Board of Education or a school district
5 board of education from utilizing private, local, or federal funds
6 to implement the provisions of this section.
7 G. The State Board of Education shall promulgate rules to
8 implement the provisions of this section, which shall include
9 requirements for instructional time for summer academy programs,
10 teacher qualifications, and evaluation of student achievement as a
11 result of summer academy programs or other optional programs.
